title: For Sale:  Hornady Titanium Nitride Pistol Dies
postcontent:
I've been reloading poly- and powder-coated bullets more lately. They don't seem to agree with Hornady dies as much, so I'm rotating some of my sets out.  I've loaded many thousands of copper jacketed and plated (Rainier, Xtreme, Berry's) through all of these without any trouble.  I think a combination of the slightly wider diameter of the bullets and the higher friction of the surface coatings are the source of the problems, but I digress.  I still use my Hornady die sets for jacketed rifle bullets.  The 9mm and .45 ACP sets each come with a Lee Factory Crimp Die.  Note that the .40 S&W dies do not specify a taper crimp like the newer sets do.  Whatever type of crimp (roll, maybe?) they perform has been perfectly adequate in every handgun I've run, from Sigs to CZ's to FN's to Glocks.  The dies have some tool marks on them, and despite my best efforts to keep them dry, they are starting to show some discolored area that are probably going to become rust spots someday.  All have the Titanium Nitride sizing rings, so you don't have to lubricate your cases when sizing.  The Sure-Loc die locking rings are all included.  Prices are as follows:
9mm Luger w/LEE FCD - $30.45 ACP w/LEE FCD - $30.40 S&W, no FCD - $20Take all three sets for $70!
They ain't pretty anymore, and I've certainly gotten my use out of them.  If you're new to reloading and don't want to spend a lot of your startup costs, the break-even on these dies is going to be a lot lower for you.  I'd also be happy to give a new reloader a hand setting up.

title: For Sale:  H&K VP9 LE 3mags
postcontent: Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK “light pull” trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun.HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset.The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break.
